Coldwater Creek, MGP Ingredients, Macy’s: U.S. Equity Movers

-- B y   N i k o l a j   G a m m e l t o f t   a n d   J e f f   K e a r n s
-- 
2011-09-01T20:12:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-31/bny-mellon-cooper-greif-saic-zumiez-u-s-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in U.S. trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of 4 p.m. in  New York .  Ciena Corp. (CIEN)   jumped 20 percent, the most in the
Russell 1000 Index, to $14.71. The maker of network gear
reported third-quarter earnings of 8 cents a share. Analysts had
estimated an 8-cent loss on average.  Coldwater Creek Inc. (CWTR)   fell 16 percent to 89 cents,
the third-biggest retreat in the Russell 2000 Index. The
clothing retailer reported a second-quarter loss of 27 cents a
share, missing the average analyst estimate by 46 percent,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Gap Inc. (GPS)   lost 3 percent, the most since Aug. 18,
to $16.03. The largest U.S. apparel chain reported sales at its
stores open more than one year fell 6 percent, more than the 3.9
percent decline estimated by analysts.  Goldman Sachs Group Inc. (GS)   slipped 3.5 percent to
$112.16, the biggest decline since Aug. 22. The firm was
downgraded to “hold” from “buy” at ISI Group Inc. The 12-
month share-price estimate is $135. The New York-based bank also
agreed to pay future penalties and review foreclosures so that
victims of wrongful seizures can be compensated.  Greif Inc. (GEF)   fell 10 percent, the most since October
2008, to $50.12. The maker of shipping and packaging reported
third-quarter adjusted earnings of $1.18 a share, missing the
average analyst estimate of $1.33.  Macy’s Inc. (M)   rose 2.1 percent to $26.49, the highest
price since Aug. 5. The retailer said sales climbed 5 percent,
topping the 4.3 percent average estimate.  MGP Ingredients Inc. (MGPI)   gained 10 percent, the most
since Dec. 21, to $6.75. The maker of distillery products will
pay a dividend of 5 cents a share, reflecting the company’s
“strong balance sheet,” according to a statement.  Movado Group Inc. (MOV)   climbed 10 percent to $15.20,
the highest price since Aug. 3. The watch and jewelry maker
reported second-quarter earnings of 16 cents a share, beating
the 4-cents a share profit estimated by analysts in a Bloomberg
survey.  SAIC Inc. (SAI)   tumbled 13 percent, the most since its
initial public offering in October 2006, to $12.97. The defense
contractor specializing in computer services cut its revenue
forecast for 2012 to no more than $11 billion, below an earlier
prediction of as much as $11.5 billion and the average analyst
estimate of $11.2 billion.  UTI Worldwide Inc. (UTIW)   rallied 13 percent, the
second-most in the Russell 1000 Index, to $15.32. The air and
ocean freight logistics company reported second-quarter profit
of 24 cents a share, compared with an average analyst estimate
in a Bloomberg survey of 21 cents a share.  To contact the reporters on this story:
